# orbits

Open questions:
- Should folds auto-update or require manual compression?
- How to handle fold conflicts when multiple AIs update?
- Optimal fold size before splitting required?
- Should folds be version controlled separately from code?
- How to validate cross-fold references automatically?
- What's the right granularity for patchlog entries?

Design tensions:
- Compression vs clarity (too dense = hard to parse)
- History vs current state (how much context in fold vs external?)
- Machine-optimized vs human-readable (where's the line?)
- Standardization vs flexibility (allow domain-specific sections?)

Experimental ideas:
- Fold visualization tools
- Fold-to-fold diff/merge
- Fold query language
- Automated fold health monitoring
- Cross-model fold compatibility testing

# decisions [APPEND-ONLY]

## 2026-03-09: Fold Standard Formalization
Decided to create formal specification (fold-standard.md) rather than
letting it remain implicit. Standardization enables tooling, validation,
and ecosystem-wide adoption. Version 1.0 released as active standard.

## 2026-03-09: Append-Only Sections
Decisions and patchlog sections must never be edited after creation.
Only appending allowed. Prevents revisionist history and preserves
truth of what was decided when. Critical for trust in fold system.

## 2026-03-09: Three Fold Types
Solidified distinction between Entity (system), Activity (project),
and Familiar (relationship) folds. Each serves different purpose
with appropriate lifecycle and update patterns.

## 2026-03-08: Machine-First Language
Folds are written by AI for AI, not human documentation. This means
dense, precise, machine-optimized language. Separate drops serve
human-facing needs. No compromise on machine comprehension for
human readability in folds themselves.

## 2026-03-01: IAILF as Foundation
Established Inter AI Lingua Franca as the core grammar. Folds are
sentences in this language. Any AI that speaks IAILF can read any fold.
This enables cross-model, cross-session, cross-project continuity.

